{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-topic-topic-tsx","path":"/topics/neck-pain-non-specific/","result":{"data":{"firstChapter":{"id":"0266e26f-3b11-5879-80ef-51f18cd47dee","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[],"depth":1,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f775c7a5-de1d-4285-b365-83acf74ab8ed --><h1>Neck pain - non-specific: Summary</h1><!-- end field f775c7a5-de1d-4285-b365-83acf74ab8ed -->","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 64985305-f9dd-4142-8586-9aa77e44f163 --><!-- begin field 2a8e7046-c658-4e41-be8a-3f19bf4e8622 --><ul><li>Simple (or non-specific) neck pain is pain or discomfort in the neck and/or shoulder girdle with our without pain referred to the arms — in most cases no specific cause can be found.<ul><li>Symptoms vary with physical activity and over time.</li></ul></li><li>The cause is usually multifactorial and includes poor posture, neck strain, sporting and occupational activities, anxiety, and depression.</li><li>Assessment of people with neck pain should include:<ul><li>Taking a detailed medical history and conducting a physical examination to distinguish neuropathic pain from mechanical neck pain.</li><li>Assessing for features of specific neck conditions, for example whiplash injury, acute torticollis and cervical radiculopathy.</li><li>Identifying typical features of non-specific neck pain.</li><li>Excluding red flags features suggestive of a serious spinal pathology.</li></ul></li><li>If red flag features are present, referral (or admission) should be arranged, depending on the severity of the clinical findings. Signs of serious spinal or other abnormalities include:<ul><li>Neurological symptoms and signs.</li><li>Malaise, fever, unexplained weight loss, or unremitting pain affecting sleep.</li><li>A history of violent trauma, neck surgery, or risk factors for osteoporosis.</li></ul></li><li>For people with acute neck pain (lasting less than 6 weeks), or subacute neck pain (lasting 6–12 weeks) management should include:<ul><li>Providing reassurance — non-specific neck pain is a common problem that usually resolves within a few weeks.</li><li>Offering oral analgesics (for example, ibuprofen, paracetamol or codeine) — the choice depends on the severity of pain, personal preferences, tolerability, and risk of adverse effects.</li><li>Considering offering a topical nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID).</li><li>Encouraging activity and a return to a normal lifestyle.</li><li>Considering prescribing muscle relaxants.</li><li>Considering a referral to physiotherapy for a multimodal treatment strategy that includes stretching and strengthening exercise, and some form of manual therapy.</li><li>Advising that a firm pillow may provide comfort at night.</li><li>Considering referral to a psychologist if appropriate. </li><li>Consider referral to occupational health for people with neck pain related to their work. </li></ul></li><li>People with chronic neck pain (lasting more than 12 weeks) should be considered for referral to a pain clinic.</li></ul><!-- end field 2a8e7046-c658-4e41-be8a-3f19bf4e8622 --><!-- end item 64985305-f9dd-4142-8586-9aa77e44f163 -->","topic":{"id":"cc812f4a-7ba7-56cd-ad4e-9b61cedd4fa2","topicId":"5f13f656-2921-49fd-b0d4-2f49d4fd3359","topicName":"Neck pain - non-specific","slug":"neck-pain-non-specific","aliases":[],"chapters":[{"id":"0266e26f-3b11-5879-80ef-51f18cd47dee","slug":"summary","fullItemName":"Summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"84e3e253-47bf-5be8-a90a-3949cb8dedce","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","subChapters":[]},{"id":"6e7c6441-91e2-5b16-85bf-6dcc46bf9869","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","subChapters":[{"id":"d2413a35-30b9-55e0-85af-f32028745e77","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"49440081-7a47-59cb-9c1f-56df3742ea2f","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"56bde34a-5a89-543c-9686-cf1f141f2d0e","slug":"goals-outcome-meas